## 1. Introduction

### 1.1 Scope

This release (v1.0.3) adds project-level workflow capabilities to the Scrum Master (SM) agent and introduces jira.conf management. The SM agent can now be invoked with a project key (e.g., KSA workflow) instead of a specific ticket key, enabling project-wide ticket listing and status management. Additionally, the SM agent now creates and manages a jira.conf file to track the active project prefix.

### 1.2 Out of Scope

* Changes to other agents (BA, TA, SA, QA, DEV, DevOps, UI)
* Jira API authentication or connection configuration (handled externally by MCP server)
* Multi-project simultaneous management (only one project prefix active at a time)
* Marketplace publishing automation

### 1.3 Preliminary Requirement

* Kiro SDLC Agents extension v1.0.2 must be the current baseline
* SM agent prompt must be accessible in all 4 locations (agents, prompts, bundled resources, source)
* Jira MCP server must be configured and accessible

## 2. Business Requirements

### 2.1 High Level Process Map

The SM agent receives user input, determines if it’s ticket-level or project-level, and routes accordingly:

1. User invokes SM agent with project key + action (e.g., KSA workflow)
2. SM reads/creates jira.conf with the project prefix
3. SM queries all project tickets from Jira
4. SM displays project overview with ticket statuses and document statuses
5. SM proposes next actions to user

![Business Flow](data:image/png;base64...)

Business Flow

### 2.2 List of User Stories / Use Cases

|  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| # | Story / Use Case / Epic | Priority | Source Ticket |
| 1 | As a developer, I want to invoke SM with a project key so that I can see all tickets and their documentation status at once | MUST HAVE | KSA-13 |
| 2 | As a developer, I want SM to manage jira.conf automatically so that the project context is preserved between sessions | MUST HAVE | KSA-13 |
| 3 | As a developer, I want SM to ask before overwriting jira.conf when the project key differs so that I don’t accidentally lose my project context | MUST HAVE | KSA-13 |
| 4 | As a developer, I want the jira.conf to only contain JIRA\_PROJECT\_PREFIX so that configuration is simple and secure | SHOULD HAVE | KSA-13 |

### 2.3 Details of User Stories

#### Business Flow

**Step 1:** User invokes SM agent with input matching pattern [A-Z]+ + action (e.g., KSA workflow)

**Step 2:** SM parses input — determines it’s project-level (no ticket number)

**Step 3:** SM reads jira.conf from workspace root: - If file doesn’t exist → create it with the new project key - If project key matches → proceed normally - If project key differs → ask user before overwriting

**Step 4:** SM queries Jira for all project tickets using JQL: project = "KSA" ORDER BY key ASC

**Step 5:** SM checks documents/{TICKET}/STATUS.json for each ticket to determine documentation status

**Step 6:** SM displays project overview table with Jira status and docs status

**Step 7:** SM proposes next actions (create docs for specific ticket, batch create, or just view status)

**Note:** SM only manages one project at a time. Switching projects requires user confirmation.

#### STORY 1: Project-level Workflow

As a developer, I want to invoke SM with a project key so that I can see all tickets and their documentation status at once

**Requirement Details:**

1. SM agent must recognize input pattern [A-Z]+ (project key without ticket number) followed by an action keyword
2. Supported actions: workflow, quy trình, status, tạo tài liệu đầy đủ
3. SM must query all tickets in the project (limit 50) ordered by key ASC
4. SM must check each ticket’s documentation status by scanning documents/{TICKET}/STATUS.json or existing files
5. SM must display a formatted table showing: Ticket key, Summary, Jira Status, Docs Status

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Given SM receives KSA workflow, it queries all KSA tickets and displays overview table
2. Given SM receives KSA status, it shows the same overview without proposing actions
3. Given a project has 50+ tickets, SM limits results to 50 and indicates there are more
4. Given a ticket has BRD+FSD+TDD, docs status shows “✅ Complete”
5. Given a ticket has no documents, docs status shows “❌ No docs”
6. Given a ticket has partial documents, docs status shows “🔄 Partial (BRD only)” or similar

#### STORY 2: jira.conf Management

As a developer, I want SM to manage jira.conf automatically so that the project context is preserved between sessions

**Requirement Details:**

1. jira.conf is located at workspace root
2. File contains only JIRA\_PROJECT\_PREFIX={PROJECT\_KEY}
3. File has a comment header explaining its purpose
4. SM creates the file if it doesn’t exist when invoked with project-level input
5. SM reads the file on every project-level invocation to verify project context

**Data Fields:**

|  |  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Field | Type | Required | Description | Example |
| JIRA\_PROJECT\_PREFIX | String | Yes | Active project key for SM agent scope | KSA |

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Given jira.conf doesn’t exist and SM receives KSA workflow, SM creates jira.conf with JIRA\_PROJECT\_PREFIX=KSA
2. Given jira.conf exists with JIRA\_PROJECT\_PREFIX=KSA and SM receives KSA workflow, SM proceeds normally
3. Given jira.conf exists with JIRA\_PROJECT\_PREFIX=ICL2 and SM receives KSA workflow, SM asks user before overwriting
4. Given user confirms project switch, SM updates jira.conf to new project key
5. Given user declines project switch, SM cancels the current command

#### STORY 3: Project Key Conflict Resolution

As a developer, I want SM to ask before overwriting jira.conf when the project key differs so that I don’t accidentally lose my project context

**Requirement Details:**

1. When project key in input differs from jira.conf, SM must display a warning
2. Warning must show current project key and proposed new key
3. User must be given numbered options to choose from
4. Only after user confirms does SM update the file

**UI Specifications:**

|  |  |  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| No. | Name | Type | Required | Description | Note |
| 1 | Warning message | Text | Yes | Shows current vs proposed project key | Format: “⚠️ jira.conf hiện tại có JIRA\_PROJECT\_PREFIX=OLD\_KEY…” |
| 2 | Option 1 | Choice | Yes | Switch to new project | “Đổi sang {NEW\_KEY} (cập nhật jira.conf)” |
| 3 | Option 2 | Choice | Yes | Keep current project | “Giữ nguyên {OLD\_KEY} (hủy lệnh hiện tại)” |

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Given project key conflict, SM displays warning with both keys visible
2. Given user selects option 1, SM updates jira.conf and proceeds with new project
3. Given user selects option 2, SM cancels and keeps existing jira.conf unchanged

#### STORY 4: Simplified jira.conf Format

As a developer, I want the jira.conf to only contain JIRA\_PROJECT\_PREFIX so that configuration is simple and secure

**Requirement Details:**

1. Previous versions had JIRA\_BASE\_URL in jira.conf — this has been removed
2. Only JIRA\_PROJECT\_PREFIX remains as the single configuration value
3. No URLs, tokens, or sensitive data in jira.conf
4. Comment header explains the file’s purpose

**Validation Rules:**

* jira.conf must not contain JIRA\_BASE\_URL (removed in this version)
* jira.conf must not contain any URL patterns
* jira.conf must not contain any token/secret patterns
* JIRA\_PROJECT\_PREFIX value must match pattern [A-Z][A-Z0-9\_]+

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Given a fresh installation, jira.conf only contains comment header + JIRA\_PROJECT\_PREFIX
2. Given an old jira.conf with JIRA\_BASE\_URL, SM overwrites with simplified format (only JIRA\_PROJECT\_PREFIX)
3. Given jira.conf content, no sensitive data (URLs, tokens) is present

